author: {'id': 1066970907, 'name': 'Nancy Sasso'}
body:
Press release  MOONLIGHT FLIGHT  Warner Theatre's 2024 Gala Celebration  Saturday, May 18, 2024  Sponsored by Torrington Savings Bank
 Torrington, CT – Embark on a celestial journey with the Warner Theatre's most magnificent fundraising event of the year, Moonlight Flight. The 2024 Gala Celebration will be held on Saturday May 18 in the Carole & Ray Neag Performing Arts Center.
  Beginning at 5 pm, indulge in a soirée of hors d'oeuvres, cocktails, and the enchanting music of MJ Vaciaunas. During the cocktail hour, attendees will have the opportunity to sign up for exclusive parties and bid on exciting silent auction experiences. The evening will continue in the Nancy Marine Studio Theatre, transformed into a celestial dining experience, with an open bar, sumptuous dinner, live entertainment by the Gatsby Gang Jazz Band, a live auction emceed by Eric Hummel, and a presentation unveiling the Warner's path forward.
  Don't miss this otherworldly celebration in May - join the Warner Theatre for a Moonlight Flight experience that transcends the ordinary! The Warner Theatre's 2024 Gala premier sponsor is Torrington Savings Bank.
  Tickets are $200 per person. To reserve a table or to sponsor the 2024 Gala, please call Lesley Budny at 860-489-7180 x 1020.
  We've removed the ability to reply as we work to make improvements.

author: {'id': 953818, 'name': 'Bill Cloutier'}
body:
The Susan B. Anthony Project in Torrington received a $10,000 grant from Torrington Savings Bank in support of the agency’s Outreach and Prevention Education Program.

The agency provides domestic and sexaul violence prevention programming to 18 towns and two cities in Northwest Connecticut

author: {'id': 1002191859}
body:
This is a carousel. Use Next and Previous buttons to navigate More than 1,800 people turned out for the 11th Annual Litchfield Hills BrewFest
at Ski Sundown, presented June 11 by Torrington Savings Bank.The 10th annual Litchfield Hills Brew Fest was held on Saturday, Aug 28, 2021 at Ski Sundown in New Hartford, Conn. The event featured beer and food from several local food trucks. Proceeds from the event were donated to St. Maron Church, Brooker Memorial and STRIDE Adaptive Sports. Were you SEEN?
 SALISBURY — Beer, brats and live music will be featured at the 14th annual Brew-Ski Fest, which returns to Satre Hill from 1-4 p.m. Oct. 8.
 Live music will be performed by local favorite, Steve Dunn.
 Tickets for Brew-Ski Fest are $30 per person in advance and are available at Stateline Wine and Spirits in Canaan, at 860 824-7295. Tickets are $35 at the gate.
 The tented tasting will be held rain or shine.
 Proceeds from the Brew-Ski events benefit SWSA’s youth ski programs.
 Go to www.eventbrite.com/e/brew-ski-fest-2023-tickets-711440115537 to reserve in advance.

body:
TORRINGTON — The Warner Theatre Stage Company recently announced its season of shows for 2024.

The 2024 season features five productions, including a musical in the Oneglia Auditorium (Main Stage), sponsored by Torrington Savings Bank, and four productions in the Nancy Marine Studio Theatre sponsored by Northwest Community Bank.



The 2024 Stage @ the Warner Season includes the following productions:



"The Irish and How They Got That Way" by Frank McCourt, with original musical arrangements by Rusty Magee. The musical is presented by special arrangement with The Irish Repertory Theatre Company, Inc. Performances will be given March 2-17 in the studio theater.



"Love, Sex and the IRS" by Billy Van Zandt and Jane Milmore will be presented May 4-12 in the studio theater.



"School of Rock" based on the Paramount movie by Mike White, book by Julian Fellowes, lyrics by Glenn Slater, and new music by Andrew Lloyd Webber, runs from Aug. 3-11 in the Oneglia Auditorium.

The Warner Theatre's 13th Annual International Playwrights Festival is set for Oct. 11-12 in the studio theater and featuring one-act plays by writers from around the country.



"Dracula" adapted from Bram Stoker’s novel by Jana Beagley, will be presented Oct. 25-Nov. 2 in the studio theater.

Season subscriptions are now available and include early access to premium seating and discounted tickets for Stage @ The Warner productions, the ability to exchange tickets for other Stage @ The Warner productions at no cost, and 5 percent off all Warner Theatre ticket purchases through June 30, 2024. Certain restrictions may apply; call the box office for details. Subscriptions must be purchased by Aug. 1 to receive these benefits.



Tickets to Stage @ the Warner’s 2024 season will be on sale to the public on Aug. 13.

For information. go to warnertheatre.org, or call 860-489-7180.

body:
The Susan B. Anthony Project is holding the annual fundraiser, 'Walk a Mile in Her Shoes'which challenges teams of walkers to wear red high heels
and raise funds for the agency to help survivors of domestic violence. Pictured is the team for Torrington Savings Bank.
 TORRINGTON — Susan B. Anthony Project’s 6th annual Walk a Mile in Her Shoes will return May 21 to the center of Litchfield. The Walk is the largest annual fundraising event for SBAP, which provides crisis and support services to domestic and sexual violence victims in northwest Connecticut.
 During the walk, men and boys lead the way on the road to end interpersonal violence by literally walking a mile in women’s high heeled shoes. All genders, ages, and abilities are welcome to participate, and the high heeled shoes are optional.
 While participants are encouraged to join live event on May 21, options are still available for those who wish to take part virtually. Red high heels are available to Walkers who wish to walk an actual mile around Litchfield center, or simply for photo opportunities to raise awareness. Groups may also choose to host their own team walks on a day and place of their choosing, with assistance and support from SBAP staff.
 In addition to walking and fundraising as an individual or as part of a team, those interested in supporting the event and SBAP’s services are invited to sponsor the walk, pledge a walker, place an ad in the event program, purchase merchandise, make a general donation, or spread the word about the event and raise awareness about the issues of domestic and sexual violence in our community.
 Susan B. Anthony Project’s 6th annual Walk a Mile in Her Shoes is sponsored by SBAP Agency Sponsors Dymax Corporation, M&T Bank, Northwest Community Bank and Its Divisions, O&G Industries, Pillar to Post Home Inspectors, Thomaston Savings Bank, Torrington Savings Bank, twenty2 wallpaper, Union Savings Bank, and Webster Bank, and by Event Sponsors The BakeHouse, Beauty Mark Tattooing, Kirstin Etela, Forman School, Gengras Subaru, RAR Excavating, Sullivan Automotive Group, and Tile America. Sponsorship opportunities are still available to interested businesses and individuals.
 All details for Susan B. Anthony Project’s Walk a Mile in Her Shoes are available at www.sbaproject.org/walkamile. For more information or questions about the Walk, contact Gina Devaux at gdevaux@sbaproject.org or Ashley Cerruto at acerruto@sbaproject.org, or call 860-489-3798.
 Walk a Mile in Her Shoes, created by Frank Baird in 2001, is an international men’s march where men and boys lead the way on the road to end sexual and domestic violence by walking a mile in women’s high heels. Created by men, the Walk gives participants the opportunity to get their communities talking about a difficult subject while increasing awareness of the problem, offering opportunities for healing, and demonstrating men’s willingness to walk with women and children as allies, advocates, and survivors. Learn more at www.walkamileinhershoes.org.
 For more information about the services and programs offered by SBAP, visit www.sbaproject.org, or call 860-489-3798. The 24-hour crisis line is 860-482-7133.

summary: {'sentences': ["The Susan B. Anthony Project is holding the annual fundraiser, 'Walk a Mile in Her Shoes'which challenges teams of walkers to wear red high heels\nand raise funds for the agency to help survivors of domestic violence.", 'Susan B. Anthony Project’s 6th annual Walk a Mile in Her Shoes is sponsored by SBAP Agency Sponsors Dymax Corporation, M&T Bank, Northwest Community Bank and Its Divisions, O&G Industries, Pillar to Post Home Inspectors, Thomaston Savings Bank, Torrington Savings Bank, twenty2 wallpaper, Union Savings Bank, and Webster Bank, and by Event Sponsors The BakeHouse, Beauty Mark Tattooing, Kirstin Etela, Forman School, Gengras Subaru, RAR Excavating, Sullivan Automotive Group, and Tile America.', 'Walk a Mile in Her Shoes, created by Frank Baird in 2001, is an international men’s march where men and boys lead the way on the road to end sexual and domestic violence by walking a mile in women’s high heels.', 'In addition to walking and fundraising as an individual or as part of a team, those interested in supporting the event and SBAP’s services are invited to sponsor the walk, pledge a walker, place an ad in the event program, purchase merchandise, make a general donation, or spread the word about the event and raise awareness about the issues of domestic and sexual violence in our community.\n ', 'TORRINGTON — Susan B. Anthony Project’s 6th annual Walk a Mile in Her Shoes will return May 21 to the center of Litchfield.']}
title: Torrington domestic violence agency holding annual charity walk

body:
AUDITIONS ANNOUNCED FOR  THE SPONGEBOB MUSICAL  Based on the Series by Stephen Hillenburg
 Performances: July 29 - August 13 in the Warner Theatre's Oneglia Auditorium, Sponsored by Torrington Savings Bank
  Director: Joe Guttadauro | Music Director: Dan Ringuette
  Choreographer: Caitlin Beaudry | Production Stage Manager: Craig Clavette
  Torrington, CT – Stage @ The Warner will hold auditions for its summer musical production of THE SPONGEBOB MUSICAL, Tuesday, May 2 and Wednesday, May 3 starting at 7 pm, by appointment. Auditions will be held at the Warner Theatre Center for Arts Education. Performances are July 29 - August 13 in the Oneglia Auditorium (Main Stage).
  Those interested in auditioning must schedule an audition time and review guidelines online at Available roles, audition times, and audition materials are available online.
  Video auditions will be accepted for those not able to attend the audition dates in person. Please submit video auditions to by 6 pm on Wednesday, May 3.
  The Warner is seeking a diverse company of actors, age 16+. Actors of all ethnicities and genders will be equally considered for all roles and are encouraged to audition. All roles are open. Ages listed are “stage ages” so older/younger performers will be considered. Additionally, roles may be cast without callbacks.
  Callbacks (if needed) will be Tuesday May 9 beginning at 7 pm.
  PERFORMANCE DATES
  Saturday, July 29 - 8 pm
  Sunday, July 30 - 2 pm
  Friday, August 4 - 8 pm
  Saturday, August 5 - 2 pm
  Sunday, August 6 (sensory friendly) - 2 pm
  Friday, August 11 - 8 pm
  Saturday, August 12 - 2 pm
  Sunday, August 13 - 2 pm
  The Warner Stage Company is a regional community theatre company and does not offer compensation or housing for performers.
  ABOUT THE SPONGEBOB MUSICAL
  The stakes are higher than ever in this dynamic stage musical, as SpongeBob and all of Bikini Bottom face the total annihilation of their undersea world. Chaos erupts. Lives hang in the balance. And just when all hope seems lost, a most unexpected hero rises up and takes center stage. The power of optimism really can save the world!

title: 2023 Update with Torrington Savings Bank

author: {'id': 1002523758}
body:
BRISTOL – The Bristol Blues revealed their new mascot Wednesday and the name has been chosen by popular vote after the Thanksgiving “Battle for the Bell.”

“Mojo,” a wolf with a cool hat and shades, suspenders and a bowtie, came to the local branch of Torrington Savings Bank, the postseason sponsor of the Blues, to “open a bank account.” There, he was welcomed by Torrington Savings Bank President and CEO Lesa Vanotti and her staff.

“We’re proud to be a sponsor of the Blues and very excited to meet Mojo,” Vanotti said.

Sarah Lucian, community relations director for the Bristol Blues, said the team is excited to partner with Torrington Savings Bank and that’s why they chose the branch as the spot to reveal the name of their new mascot.

Mojo made his first appearance during the Battle for the Bell at Muzzy Field and fans were able to vote on a giant poster board for the mascot’s new name.

“Third place had 199 votes, so your name is not Jasper,” Lucian said to the mascot. “Second place had 290 votes, so your name is not Ace. With 347 votes, you’re Mojo.”

Lucian said young Bristol Blues fans tipped the scale in the naming contest.

“Just about every kid voted for Mojo,” she said.

Lucian wished everyone in attendance “Happy Holidays” and said the Blues are excited for their next season. Following a strong season, where the team finished 32-12, the nonprofit baseball team is headed into its eighth season in June 2023. Tickets will remain $6.

The Blues, Lucian said, had been working on an updated mascot after the previous mascot “BB” went into “retirement.” He left on a high note, with last year’s season seeing high fan attendance and the team holding several “promo nights” to support a variety of causes.

For more information on the Bristol Blues, visit bristolblues.pointstreaksites.com.

Brian M. Johnson can be reached at 860-973-1806 or bjohnson@bristolpress.com.

summary:
{'sentences': ['BRISTOL – The Bristol Blues revealed their new mascot Wednesday and the name has been chosen by popular vote after the Thanksgiving “Battle for the Bell.”

“Mojo,” a wolf with a cool hat and shades, suspenders and a bowtie, came to the local branch of Torrington Savings Bank, the postseason sponsor of the Blues, to “open a bank account.”', 'Sarah Lucian, community relations director for the Bristol Blues, said the team is excited to partner with Torrington Savings Bank and that’s why they chose the branch as the spot to reveal the name of their new mascot.

', 'With 347 votes, you’re Mojo.”

Lucian said young Bristol Blues fans tipped the scale in the naming contest.

', 'Lucian wished everyone in attendance “Happy Holidays” and said the Blues are excited for their next season.', 'Mojo made his first appearance during the Battle for the Bell at Muzzy Field and fans were able to vote on a giant poster board for the mascot’s new name.

']}
title: The Bristol Press - City fans choose 'Mojo' as name for new Bristol Blues mascot

body:
This is a carousel. Use Next and Previous buttons to navigate
From left are Greg Brisco, CEO, Northwestern CT YMCA; Lesa Vanotti, President & CEO, Torrington Savings Bank; Tina Milanesi, TSFoundation Coordinator; Jeff Geddes, VP Community Relations & CRA Officer, Torrington Savings Bank.Jack Mac Scramble for ALS committee member Dave Paniati holds up the check with the final total as Jack’s wife, Chris McCarthy, announces it to the guests.  The Cancer Care Fund of the Litchfield Hills recently accepted a check for $6,000 from the Torrington Elks Lodge. From left are Rich Slevinsky, Past Exalted Ruler of the Elks, Susan Smith, Executive Director of the Cancer Care Fund, Dan Fisher, Esteemed Leading Knight of the Elks, and Danny Hartnett, Cancer Care Fund board member.  TORRINGTON — The Torrington Savings Foundation announced grants totaling $67,748 during its most recent grant cycle. The awards sustain the mission of investing in community revitalization through neighborhood renewal and education initiatives, members said.  One such grant is in support of the Northwestern CT YMCA, which is celebrating its 100-year anniversary of the Prospect Street, Torrington location in 2022. While the YMCA supports thousands of youths at this location, they lack an outdoor athletic field to support this facet of their youth program. This grant will allow the rehabilitation of the Railroad Square Recreation area. Additional funding will benefit the expansion of the Youth Service Bureau’s Rising Start Camp facility.

summary: {'sentences': ['This is a carousel.', 'The Cancer Care Fund of the Litchfield Hills recently accepted a check for $6,000 from the Torrington Elks Lodge.', 'One such grant is in support of the Northwestern CT YMCA, which is celebrating its 100-year anniversary of the Prospect Street, Torrington location in 2022.', 'Use Next and Previous buttons to navigate\nFrom left are Greg Brisco, CEO, Northwestern CT YMCA; Lesa Vanotti, President & CEO, Torrington Savings Bank; Tina Milanesi, TSFoundation Coordinator; Jeff Geddes, VP Community Relations & CRA Officer, Torrington Savings Bank.', 'From left are Rich Slevinsky, Past Exalted Ruler of the Elks, Susan Smith, Executive Director of the Cancer Care Fund, Dan Fisher, Esteemed Leading Knight of the Elks, and Danny Hartnett, Cancer Care Fund board member.  ']}
